Chosen topic: Universal Basic Income

Research should be boiled down to 2-3 key points in lieu of numerous AI-assisted ideas

It can be said that the people that desire something the most are the ones that such programs/subsidies are tailored to. For instance, the Universal Basic Income proposal has not been put into action yet; such a “liberal fantasy” is mainly directed towards those without jobs or susceptible to losing their jobs, especially in the midst of rising AI automation in the workplace.
The creative medium I would like to use to convey my gathered ideas is through a journal/diary.
People of many, if not all, backgrounds/professions have spoken up—whether it be from recent times or far back into the past, about raising concerns in the rising wave of AI. Workers of various fields of interest, stationed at companies once fully operated by its own workforce composed of collective human effort and due diligence, have since been on the receiving end of displacement from or replacement of the employees’ jobs in question. Universal basic income comes into play in the midst of weighing many different facets and taking what we would like to think are well-informed approaches. 
From an analytical standpoint, levying higher taxes (especially for high tax brackets) isn’t likely.
Much like how artificial intelligence was jokingly proposed long ago to be able to evolve into something too dangerous to contain, universal basic income has also been hailed as a sort of “utopian,” if you will, method of stabilizing the job market alongside the broader economy (as a whole) of societies across the globe. Now, both concepts are not only realizing ever so quickly, individuals are also realizing that the contrasting programs must complement each other in moving forward and making progress. 
When put together, AI and what it entails for the future can be deemed as a trailblazer. At the same time, those that may stand in the way of it all cannot become sitting ducks that are trampled over.


